ritish. At the same time, with the 1962 Commonwealth Immigrants Act, the British government began to implement restrictions aimed at slowing the migration of British subjects of colour. In all three nations, these policies were aimed at the preservation of nations imagined as white, revealing the persistence of the racial ideologies of empire across the era of decolonisation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2022. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aRhodesia.  aUnited Kingdom.  aZimbabwe.  aapartheid South Africa.  adecolonisation.  aemigration.  aimmigration.  amigration.  arace.1 aSmith, Jean P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614549940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526145499423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526145499/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles